What is Data Science?

The Two Tribes of Data Science

Why Data Science Now?

The rise in data science has been driven by the merging of several disciplines into one meta-discipline and several significant shifts in foundational disciplines:

  • Computer Science / Software Engineering:
    • Git Repos and Open Source Projects
    • (Massively) Parallel Computing
    • Big Data
    • Amazon Web Services (Cloud Computing)


  • Math / Statistics: Rise of open source software communities (R, Julia, etc.) for math and statistics.


  • Data Visualization (vs. Graphics): Use of a more powerful medium (html vs Word) to communicate the insights contained in models/data (many examples to be shown today).

How Do I Become a Data Scientist?

- Source: https://datafloq.com/read/long-road-big-data-scientist-infographic/423

No Really - How Do I Become a Data Scientist?

  • If you aren't moving forward, you're moving backwards (learn something every day).

  • DS requires a mix of education (understanding of concepts) and training (a collection of skills).

  • Google, stack overflow, curiousity and perserverance can often substitute for specific training (just get after it); education is hard to sub.

  • Master the fundamentals first: statistics and programming (R or Python).

  • Master one language (R recommended for ORSAs) before adding another (Python, Scala, javascript, etc.).

  • Data science is a team sport: join a team!

  • Read, learn, comment, contribute: dscoe.army.mil.

Expectation Management

What you should not expect from today:

  • A comprehensive review
  • A class on how to program
  • A class that troubleshoots your code
  • Any in-depth analysis or math review

What you should expect from today:

  • A very interactive experience
  • Try the code!
  • Follow the links!
  • A collection of reproducible examples
  • A forum to ask questions
  • Access to folks who are doing this stuff now (network)
  • A better understanding of data science
  • A head start on building your skill set!
